<div id="review_6109756" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/6109756" />
    <a title="Josh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/373817-josh"><img alt="Josh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1189627136p2/373817.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/6109756?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Josh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Josh" href="/user/show/373817-josh">Josh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">lowbrow readers in highbrow disguises</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer6109756" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17433172149403570499">I normally wouldnât pick up something like this, but it was given to me as a gift, so I cracked it. It took me until about half-way through before I realized that it was the basis for the Johnny Depp/Roman Polanski flop âThe Ninth Gate.â (Which I&apos;ve yet to see).<br/><br/><i>The Club Dumas</i> was probably only the second detective novel Iâve read in the past five years, the other being Jonathan Lethemâs <i>Motherless Brooklyn</i>. While the novels have very little in common, I couldnât help but notice the formulaic sim</span>
  <span id="freeText17433172149403570499" style="display:none">I normally wouldnât pick up something like this, but it was given to me as a gift, so I cracked it. It took me until about half-way through before I realized that it was the basis for the Johnny Depp/Roman Polanski flop âThe Ninth Gate.â (Which I've yet to see).<br /><br /><i>The Club Dumas</i> was probably only the second detective novel Iâve read in the past five years, the other being Jonathan Lethemâs <i>Motherless Brooklyn</i>. While the novels have very little in common, I couldnât help but notice the formulaic similarities, and though one is about a rare book collector in Spain and the other about a Touretteâs-inflicted driver in New York, neither seems able to avoid (or resist?) the clichÃ©s of the genre: <br /><br />â¢Both begin with the death of an older patron of the protagonist.<br /><br />â¢Our bumbling protagonist is then hesitantly lured into investigating the crime.<br /><br />â¢The protagonist is met with resistance by the dead manâs âsultry widow with a murky pastâ who tries to seduce him, but doesn't. (It is later revealed that the widow is sleeping with the protagonistâs presumed only ally(s).)<br /><br />â¢A beautiful younger woman (both described as being between 18 and 20 with short, black hair) comes out of nowhere and becomes instantly infatuated with our admittedly unattractive protagonist for reasons never stated.<br /><br />â¢A shadowy, violent figure stalks, then attacks our protagonist. He is rescued by the younger woman.<br /><br />â¢Clues lead him to a city up the coast where the main events of the plot are revealed to be the machinations of a clandestine, conspiratorial organization. <br /><br />Unfortunately, the strikingly familiar formula makes the only original and interesting aspects of each â Lionelâs battle with Touretteâs befuddling his efforts to solve the crime, or The Club Dumasâ references to esoterica and arcane literature which are clearly designed to appeal to pretentious literati (okay, so it worked ;P) â seem like little more than window dressing, leaving the core of the novel a warmed-over re-run. Hell, even the DaVinci Code contained most of the above formula.<br /><br />Motherless Brooklyn, with its exploration of small-time crime syndicates and short, sporadic sub-chapters (some no more than a few sentences long) which parallel the main character's own tourettic outbursts, was clearly the better written of the two. The Club Dumasâ constant dwelling upon âcluesâ which have all the subtlety of an out-of-control Sherman tank, results in the reader knowing exactly what is going to happen before they're even half-way through. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17433172149403570499" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


